
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h1 id="Mapping-in-Python-with-geopandas">Mapping in Python with <code>geopandas</code><a class="anchor-link" href="#Mapping-in-Python-with-geopandas">&#182;</a></h1>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[1]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="o">%</span><span class="k">matplotlib</span> inline

<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">matplotlib.pyplot</span> <span class="kn">as</span> <span class="nn">plt</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">geopandas</span> <span class="kn">as</span> <span class="nn">gpd</span>
<span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pysal</span> <span class="kn">as</span> <span class="nn">ps</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">pysal.contrib.viz</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">mapping</span> <span class="k">as</span> <span class="n">maps</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>In this lab, we will learn how to load, manipulate and visualize spatial data. In some senses, spatial data have become so pervasive that nowadays, they are usually included simply as "one more column" in a table. However, <em>spatial is special</em> and there are few aspects in which geographic data differ from standard numerical tables. In this session, we will extend the skills developed in the previous one about non-spatial data, and combine them. In the process, we will discover that, although with some particularities, dealing with spatial data in Python largely resembles dealing with non-spatial data. For example, in this lab you will learn to make slick maps like this one with just a few commands:</p>
<p><img src="figs/lab03_liverpool_lsoas.png" alt=""></p>
<p>Or interactive ones like this one where the smallest areas of Liverpool are highlighted in red:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[2]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="c1"># Please note this will not display on your machine as it depends on an external file</span>
<span class="c1"># A rendered version can be found on the HTML or PDF versions of this notebook</span>
<span class="kn">from</span> <span class="nn">IPython.display</span> <span class="kn">import</span> <span class="n">IFrame</span>
<span class="n">IFrame</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s2">&quot;figs/lab03_liverpool_smallest.html&quot;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">width</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">560</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">height</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">315</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[2]:</div>

<div class="output_html rendered_html output_subarea output_execute_result">

        <iframe
            width="560"
            height="315"
            src="figs/lab03_liverpool_smallest.html"
            frameborder="0"
            allowfullscreen
        ></iframe>
        
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>To learn these concepts, we will be playing again with the geography of Liverpool. In particular we will use Census geographies (Available as part of the Census Data pack used before, see <a href="https://data.cdrc.ac.uk/dataset/cdrc-2011-census-data-packs-for-local-authority-district-liverpool-e08000012">link</a>) and Ordnance Survey geospatial data, available to download also from the CDRC data store (<a href="https://data.cdrc.ac.uk/dataset/cdrc-2015-os-geodata-pack-liverpool-e08000012">link</a>). To make the rest of the notebook easier to follow, let us set the paths to the main two folders here. We will call the path to the Liverpool Census pack <code>lcp_dir</code>, and that to the OS geodata <code>los_dir</code>:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[3]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">lcp_dir</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;../../../../data/Liverpool/&#39;</span>
<span class="n">los_dir</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;../../../../data/E08000012_OS/&#39;</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Loading-up-spatial-data">Loading up spatial data<a class="anchor-link" href="#Loading-up-spatial-data">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The easiest way to get from a file to a quick visualization of the data is by loading it as a <code>GeoDataFrame</code> and calling the <code>plot</code> command. The main library employed for all of this is <code>geopandas</code> which is a geospatial extension of the <code>pandas</code> library, already introduced before. <code>geopandas</code> supports exactly the same functionality that <code>pandas</code> does (in fact since it is built on top of it, so most of the underlying machinery is pure <code>pandas</code>), plus a wide range of spatial counterparts that make manipulation and general "munging" of spatial data as easy as non-spatial tables.</p>
<p>In two lines of code, we will obtain a graphical representation of the spatial data contained in a file that can be in many formats; actually, since it uses the same drivers under the hood, you can load pretty much the same kind of vector files that QGIS permits. Let us start by plotting single layers in a crude but quick form, and we will build style and sophistication into our plots later on.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Polygons</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Let us begin with the most common type of spatial data in the social science: polygons. For example, we can load the geography of LSOAs in Liverpool with the following lines of code:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[4]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">lsoas_link</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lcp_dir</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">&#39;shapefiles/Liverpool_lsoa11.shp&#39;</span>
<span class="n">lsoas</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_file</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">lsoas_link</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now <code>lsoas</code> is a <code>GeoDataFrame</code>. Very similar to a traditional, non-spatial <code>DataFrame</code>, but with an additional column called <code>geometry</code>:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[5]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

    </tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
</div>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>This allows us to quickly produce a plot by executing the following line:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[6]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<p>This might not be the most aesthetically pleasant visual representation of the LSOAs geography, but it is hard to argue it is not quick to produce. We will work on styling and customizing spatial plots later on.</p>

</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Displaying lines is as straight-forward as polygons. To load railway tunnels in Liverpool and name the rows after the <code>id</code> column (or to "index" them):</p>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[8]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">rwy_tun</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_file</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">los_dir</span> <span class="o">+</span> <span class="s1">&#39;RailwayTunnel.shp&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">rwy_tun</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">rwy_tun</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;id&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">rwy_tun</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">info</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Again, this is not the prettiest way to display the roads maybe, and you might want to change a few parameters such as colors, etc. All of this is possible, as we will see below, but this gives us an easy check of what lines look like.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<hr>
<p><strong>[Optional exercise]</strong></p>
<p>Obtain the graphical representation of the line with <code>id</code> = <code>0ACD196C32214F8DE050A00A568A6F6F</code>.</p>
<!--
rwy_tun.loc['0ACD196C313D4F8DE050A00A568A6F6F', 'geometry']
-->

<hr>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Points</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Finally, points follow a similar structure. If we want to represent named places in Liverpool:</p>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Styling-plots">Styling plots<a class="anchor-link" href="#Styling-plots">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>It is possible to tweak several aspects of a plot to customize if to particular needs. In this section, we will explore some of the basic elements that will allow us to obtain more compelling maps.</p>
<p><strong>NOTE</strong>: some of these variations are very straightforward while others are more intricate and require tinkering with the internal parts of a plot. They are not necessarily organized by increasing level of complexity.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Changing transparency</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The intensity of color of a polygon can be easily changed through the <code>alpha</code> attribute in plot. This is specified as a value betwee zero and one, where the former is entirely transparent while the latter is the fully opaque (maximum intensity):</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[13]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">alpha</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Removing axes</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Although in some cases, the axes can be useful to obtain context, most of the times maps look and feel better without them. Removing the axes involves wrapping the plot into a figure, which takes a few more lines of aparently useless code but that, in time, it will allow you to tweak the map further and to create much more flexible designs:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[15]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">axes</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_axis_off</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Let us stop for a second a study each of the previous lines:</p>
<ol>
<li>We have first created a figure named <code>f</code> with one axis named <code>ax</code> by using the command <code>plt.subplots</code> (part of the library <code>matplotlib</code>, which we have imported at the top of the notebook). Note how the method is returning two elements and we can assign each of them to objects with different name (<code>f</code> and <code>ax</code>) by simply listing them at the front of the line, separated by commas.</li>
<li>Second, we plot the geographies as before, but this time we tell the function that we want it to draw the polygons on the axis we are passing, <code>ax</code>. This method returns the axis with the geographies in them, so we make sure to store it on an object with the same name, <code>ax</code>.</li>
<li>On the third line, we effectively remove the box with coordinates.</li>
<li>Finally, we draw the entire plot by calling <code>plt.show()</code>.</li>
</ol>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Adding a title</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Adding a title is a simple extra line, if we are creating the plot within a figure, as we just did. To include text on top of the figure:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[16]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">axes</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">f</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">suptitle</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;Liverpool LSOAs&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Changing the size of the map</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The size of the plot is changed equally easily in this context. The only difference is that it is specified when we create the figure with the argument <code>figsize</code>. The first number represents the width, the X axis, and the second corresponds with the height, the Y axis.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[17]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">axes</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">)</span>

</pre></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Scaling plots</li>
</ul>
<p>You will notice that the ability to change the size of the figure is very powerful as it makes possible to obtain many different sizes and shapes for plots. However, this also may introduce some distortions in the way the shapes are represented. For example, a very wide figure can make the viewer think that polygons are in reality more "stretched out" than they are in reality:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[18]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">axes</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Although in some contexts this may be desirable (or at least, accepted), in many it will not. From a cartographic point of view, maps need to be as good representatios of reality as they can. We can ensure the scaling ratio between both axes remains fixed, whichever the shape of the figure. To do this, we only need to add a single extra line of code: <code>plt.axis("equal")</code>.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[19]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">12</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">4</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">axes</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">lims</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">axis</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;equal&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Modifying borders</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Border lines sometimes can distort or impede proper interpretation of a map. In those cases, it is useful to know how they can be modified. Although not too complicated, the way to access borders in <code>geopandas</code> is not as straightforward as it is the case for other aspects of the map, such as size or frame. Let us first see the code to make the <em>lines thinner</em> and <em>grey</em>, and then we will work our way through the different steps:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[20]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">poly</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multipolygon</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poly</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">edgecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;grey&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Note how the lines are much thinner and discreet. In addition, because of the way we plot the data, all the polygons are colored in the same (default) color, light red.</p>
<p>Let us examine line by line what we are doing in the code snippet:</p>
<ul>
<li>We begin by creating the figure (<code>f</code>) object and one axis inside it (<code>ax</code>) where we will plot the map.</li>
<li>Then, instead of calling the utility function <code>plot</code> on the <code>DataFrame</code>, we loop over every element of the column <code>geometry</code>. As we know from above, this dataset contains polygons representing areas of Liverpool, represented geometrically in polygons. For convenience, we call them in the loop <code>poly</code>.</li>
<li>Line 3 is the crucial part in the cell. In there, we plot <em>each</em> of the polygons individually, using the function <code>plot_multipolygon</code>, which in part of the <code>plotting</code> submodule in <code>geopandas</code> (which, recall, we have renamed <code>gpd</code> for convenience). The way this function works is you need to always pass the axis (<code>ax</code> in this case) where the geometry will be drawn, then the actual geometry (<code>poly</code> here), and then you can optionally pass some arguments that tweak the default appearance. Accessing each polygon at once affords us further flexibility and allows us to set the width of the border lines (<code>linewidth</code>) as well as their colors (<code>edgecolor</code>). Note that, because we are plotting at the polygon level, instead of at the <code>DataFrame</code> level, each polygon is colored in the same way.</li>
<li>Draw the map using <code>plt.show()</code>.</li>
</ul>
<p>Note that we are calling the fuction <code>plot_multipolygon</code>. This is so because we know we want to plot polygons. If instead we wanted to display lines, as those we read into <code>rwy_tun</code>, we would take a similar approach, but using <code>plot_multilinestring</code>:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[21]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">line</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">rwy_tun</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multilinestring</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;red&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Important, note that in the case of lines the parameter to control the color is simply <code>color</code>. This is because lines do not have an area, so there is no need to distinguish between the main area (<code>facecolor</code>) and the border lines (<code>edgecolor</code>).</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Choosing a single color for every polygon</li>
</ul>
<p>If you understand the logic behind plotting elements individually, as shown above, modifying the color of the polygon itself is very straightforward, you only need to tweak the parameter <code>facecolor</code> to your preferred color. For instance, let us draw the borders without coloring the polygons, leaving them white:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[22]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">poly</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multipolygon</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poly</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">facecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;white&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Transforming CRS</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>The coordindate reference system (CRS) is the way geographers and cartographers have to represent a three-dimentional object, such as the round earth, on a two-dimensional plane, such as a piece of paper or a computer screen. If the source data contain information on the CRS of the data, it is very easy to modify this in a <code>GeoDataFrame</code>. First let us check if we have the information stored properly:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[23]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">crs</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[23]:</div>


<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>{u&apos;datum&apos;: u&apos;OSGB36&apos;,
 u&apos;k&apos;: 0.9996012717,
 u&apos;lat_0&apos;: 49,
 u&apos;lon_0&apos;: -2,
 u&apos;no_defs&apos;: True,
 u&apos;proj&apos;: u&apos;tmerc&apos;,
 u&apos;units&apos;: u&apos;m&apos;,
 u&apos;x_0&apos;: 400000,
 u&apos;y_0&apos;: -100000}</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>As we can see, there is information stored about the reference system: it is using the datum "OSGB36", which is a projection in meters (<code>m</code> in units). There are also other less decipherable parameters but we do not need to worry about them right now.</p>
<p>If we want to modify this and "reproject" the polygons into a different CRS, the easiest way is to find the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Association_of_Oil_%26_Gas_Producers#European_Petroleum_Survey_Group">EPSG</a> code online (<a href="http://epsg.io/">epsg.io</a> is a good one, although there are others too). For example, if we wanted to transform the dataset into lat/lon coordinates, we would use its EPSG code, 4326:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[24]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">to_crs</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">epsg</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">4326</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">lims</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">axis</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;equal&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt"></div>

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Because the area we are visualizing is not very large, the shape of the polygons is roughly the same. However, note how the <em>scale</em> in which they are plotted differs: while before we had coordinate points ranging 332,000 to 398,000, now these are expressed in degrees, and range from -3.05 to -2,80 on the longitude, and between 53.32 and 53.48 on the latitude.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<hr>
<p><strong>[Optional exercise]</strong></p>
<p>Make a map of the LSOAs that features the following characteristics:</p>
<ul>
<li>Includes a title</li>
<li>Does not include axes frame</li>
<li>It is proportioned and has a figure size of 10 by 11.</li>
<li>Polygons are all in the color "#525252" and fully opaque.</li>
<li>Lines have a width of 0.3 and are of color "#B9EBE3"</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Composing-multi-layer-maps">Composing multi-layer maps<a class="anchor-link" href="#Composing-multi-layer-maps">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>So far we have considered many aspects of plotting <em>a single</em> layer of data. However, in many cases, an effective map will require more than one: for example we might want to display streets on top of the polygons of neighborhoods, and add a few points for specific locations we want to highlight. At the very heart of GIS is the possibility to combine spatial information from different sources by overlaying it on top of each other, and this is fully supported in Python.</p>
<p>Essentially, combining different layers on a single map boils down to adding each of them to the same axis in a sequential way, as if we were literally overlaying one on top of the previous one. For example, let us get the simplest possible plot, one with the polygons from the LSOAs and the tunnels on top of them:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[25]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">axes</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">rwy_tun</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">axes</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Because the default colors are not really designed to mix and match several layers, it is hard to tell them apart. However, we can use all the skills and tricks learned on styling a single layer, to make a multi-layer more sophisticated and, ultimately, useful.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[26]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Plot polygons in light grey</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">poly</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multipolygon</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poly</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">facecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;grey&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">alpha</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.25</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Overlay railway tunnels on top in strong green</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">line</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">rwy_tun</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multilinestring</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;green&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>

<hr>
<p><strong>[Optional exercise]</strong></p>
<p>Create a similar map to the one above, but replace the railway tunnels by the named places points used at the beginning (and saved into <code>namp</code>). Do not try to set the color to green or any other particular one, but you can play with the size of the dot.</p>
<p><strong>Pro-tip</strong>: keep in mind you are plotting points no lines, so be sure to check the help of the function <code>gpd.plotting.plot_point</code>.</p>
<!--
f, ax = plt.subplots(1)
# Plot polygons in light grey
for poly in lsoas['geometry']:
    gpd.plotting.plot_multipolygon(ax, poly, facecolor='grey', alpha=0.25, linewidth=0.1)
# Overlay points
for pt in namp['geometry']:
    gpd.plotting.plot_point(ax, pt, markersize=4)
plt.show()
-->

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Saving-maps-to-figures">Saving maps to figures<a class="anchor-link" href="#Saving-maps-to-figures">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Once we have produced a map we are content with, we might want to save it to a file so we can include it into a report, article, website, etc. Exporting maps in Python is as simple as replacing <code>plt.show</code> by <code>plt.savefig</code> at the end of the code block to specify where and how to save it. For example to save the previous map into a <code>png</code> file in the same folder where the notebook is hosted:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[27]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Plot polygons in light grey</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">poly</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multipolygon</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poly</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">facecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;grey&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">alpha</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.25</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Overlay railway tunnels on top in strong green</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">line</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">rwy_tun</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multilinestring</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;green&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">savefig</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;liverpool_railway_tunels.png&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>If you now check on the folder, you'll find a <code>png</code> (image) file with the map.</p>
<p>The command <code>plt.savefig</code> contains a large number of options and additional parameters to tweak. Given the size of the figure created is not very large, we can increase this with the argument <code>dpi</code>, which stands for "dots per inch" and it's a standard measure of resolution in images. For example, for a high definition (HD) quality image, we can use 1080:</p>
<p><strong>[Note]</strong>: if this takes too long, try with 500 instead, which will still give you a good quality image that renders more easily.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[28]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Plot polygons in light grey</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">poly</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multipolygon</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poly</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">facecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;grey&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">alpha</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.25</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Overlay railway tunnels on top in strong green</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">line</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">rwy_tun</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multilinestring</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">line</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">color</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;green&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">3</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">savefig</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;liverpool_railway_tunels.png&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">dpi</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1080</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">

<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="Manipulating-spatial-tables-(GeoDataFrames)">Manipulating spatial tables (<code>GeoDataFrames</code>)<a class="anchor-link" href="#Manipulating-spatial-tables-(GeoDataFrames)">&#182;</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Once we have an understanding of how to visually display spatial information contained, let us see how it can be combined with the operations learnt in the previous session about manipulating non-spatial tabular data. Essentially, the key is to realize that a <code>GeoDataFrame</code> contains most of its spatial information in a single column named <code>geometry</code>, but the rest of it looks and behaves exactly like a non-spatial <code>DataFrame</code> (in fact, it is). This concedes them all the flexibility and convenience that we saw in manipulating, slicing, and transforming tabular data, with the bonus that spatial data is carried away in all those steps. In addition, <code>GeoDataFrames</code> also incorporate a set of explicitly spatial operations to combine and transform data. In this section, we will consider both.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Let us refresh some of the techniques we learned in the previous session about non-spatial tabular data and see how those can be combined with the mapping of their spatial counter-parts. To do this, we will revisit the population data we explored in the previous section:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[29]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="kn">import</span> <span class="nn">pandas</span> <span class="kn">as</span> <span class="nn">pd</span>

<span class="c1"># Set the path to the location of the Liverpool Census Data-Pack,</span>
<span class="c1"># just as you did at the beginning of the previous session</span>
<span class="n">path</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="s1">&#39;../../../../data/Liverpool/&#39;</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Remember the data we want need to be extracted and renamed for the variables to have human readable names. Here we will do it all in one shot, but you can go back to the notebook of the previous session to follow the steps in more detail.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[30]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="c1"># Read original table</span>
<span class="n">lsoa_orig</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">path</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="s1">&#39;tables/QS203EW_lsoa11.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;GeographyCode&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Select necessary variables</span>
<span class="n">region_codes</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;QS203EW0002&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;QS203EW0032&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;QS203EW0045&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> \
                <span class="s1">&#39;QS203EW0063&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;QS203EW0072&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="n">lsoa_orig_sub</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoa_orig</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[:,</span> <span class="n">region_codes</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="c1"># Rename variables from codes into names</span>
<span class="n">variables</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">pd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">read_csv</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">path</span><span class="o">+</span><span class="s1">&#39;variables_description.csv&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">index_col</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">code2name</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="p">{}</span>
<span class="n">lookup_table</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">variables</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_index</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;ColumnVariableCode&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="c1"># Reindex to be able to query</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">code</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">region_codes</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="n">code2name</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">code</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lookup_table</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">loc</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">code</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;ColumnVariableDescription&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">code</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">code2name</span><span class="p">:</span>
    <span class="n">code2name</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">code</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">code2name</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="n">code</span><span class="p">]</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">replace</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;: Total&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="s1">&#39;&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">lsoa_orig_sub</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoa_orig_sub</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">rename</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">columns</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="n">code2name</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Calculate total populations by area</span>
<span class="n">lsoa_orig_sub</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;Total&#39;</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoa_orig_sub</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sum</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">axis</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">lsoa_orig_sub</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Join tabular data</li>
</ul>
<p>Now we have both tables loaded into the session: on the one hand, the spatial data are contained in <code>lsoas</code>, while all the tabular data are in <code>lsoa_orig_sub</code>. To be able to work with the two together, we need to <em>connect</em> them. In <code>pandas</code> language, this is called "join" and the key element in joins are the <em>indices</em>, the names assigned to each row of the tables. This is what we determine, for example, when we indicate <code>index_col</code> when reading a <code>csv</code>. In the case above, the index is set on <code>GeographyCode</code>. In the case of the <code>GeoDataFrame</code>, there is not any specific index, but a simple unamed sequence. The spatial table does have however a column called <code>LSOA11CD</code> which represents the code for each polygon, and this one actually matches those in <code>GeographyCode</code> in the population table.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[31]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">

    </tr>

      <td>POLYGON ((335354.015 388601.947, 335354 388602...</td>

</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Having the same column, albeit named differently, in both tables thus allows us to combine, <em>"join"</em>, the two into a single one where rows are matched that we will call <code>geo_pop</code>:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[32]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">geo_pop</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">join</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">lsoa_orig_sub</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">on</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;LSOA11CD&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">geo_pop</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[32]:</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Let us quickly run through the logic of joins:</p>
<ul>
<li>First, it is an operation in which you are "attaching" some data to a previously existing one. This does not always need to be like this but, for now, we will only consider this case. In particular, in the operation above, we are attaching the population data in <code>lsoa_orig_sub</code> to the spatial table <code>lsoas</code>.</li>
<li>Second, note how the main table does not need to be indexed in the shared column for the join to be possible, it only needs to contain it. In this case, the index of <code>lsoas</code> is a simple sequence, but the relevant codes are stored in the column <code>LSOA11CD</code>.</li>
<li>Third, the table that is being attached <em>does</em> need to be indexed on the relevant column. This is fine with us because <code>lsoa_orig_sub</code> <em>is</em> already indexed on the relevant ID codes.</li>
<li>Finally, note how the join operation contains two arguments: one is obviously the table we want to attach; the second one, preceded by "<code>on</code>" relates to the column in the main table that is required to be matched with the index of the table being attached. In this case, the relevant ID codes are in the column <code>LSOA11CD</code>, so we specify that.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>One final note, there appears to be a bug in the code that makes the joined table to loose the CRS. Reattaching it is straightforward:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[33]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">geo_pop</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">crs</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">lsoas</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">crs</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Non-spatial-manipulations">Non-spatial manipulations<a class="anchor-link" href="#Non-spatial-manipulations">&#182;</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Once we have joined spatial and non-spatial data, we can use the techniques learned in manipulating and slicing non-spatial tables to create much richer maps. In particular, let us recall the example we worked through in the previous session in which we were selecting rows based on their population characteristics. In addition to being able to to select them, now we will also be able to visualize them in maps.</p>
<p>For example, let us select again the ten smallest areas of Liverpool (note how we pass a number to <code>head</code> to keep that amount of rows):</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[34]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">smallest</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">geo_pop</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">sort</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;Total&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">10</span><span class="p">)</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Now we can make a map of Liverpool and overlay on top of them these areas:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[35]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">f</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">ax</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">subplots</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">figsize</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="mi">6</span><span class="p">))</span>
<span class="c1"># Base layer with all the areas for the background</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">poly</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">geo_pop</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multipolygon</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poly</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">facecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;black&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mf">0.025</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="c1"># Smallest areas</span>
<span class="k">for</span> <span class="n">poly</span> <span class="ow">in</span> <span class="n">smallest</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="s1">&#39;geometry&#39;</span><span class="p">]:</span>
    <span class="n">gpd</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plotting</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot_multipolygon</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">ax</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">poly</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">alpha</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">facecolor</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="s1">&#39;red&#39;</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">linewidth</span><span class="o">=</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">ax</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">set_axis_off</span><span class="p">()</span>
<span class="n">f</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">suptitle</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;Areas with smallest population&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">axis</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="s1">&#39;equal&#39;</span><span class="p">)</span>
<span class="n">plt</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">show</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<hr>
<p><strong>[Optional exercise. Difficulty: 4/5]</strong></p>
<p>Create a map of Liverpool with the two largest areas for each of the different population subgroups in a different color each.</p>
<hr>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Spatial-manipulations">Spatial manipulations<a class="anchor-link" href="#Spatial-manipulations">&#182;</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>In addition to operations purely based on values of the table, as above, <code>GeoDataFrame</code>s come built-in with a whole range of traditional GIS operations. Here we will run through a small subset of them that contains some of the most commonly used ones.</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Centroid calculation</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Sometimes it is useful to summarize a polygon into a single point and, for that, a good candidate is its centroid (almost like a spatial analogue of the average). The following command will return a <code>GeoSeries</code> (a single column with spatial data) with the centroids of a polygon <code>GeoDataFrame</code>:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[36]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">cents</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="n">geo_pop</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">centroid</span>
<span class="n">cents</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">head</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[36]:</div>


<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">
<pre>0     POINT (336154.2863649924 389733.635773753)
1    POINT (335535.9278617767 390060.8596847057)
2    POINT (335525.0607160075 389484.4020273419)
3    POINT (335117.4359614222 389195.6749620197)
4     POINT (335532.691301766 388692.8415110898)
dtype: object</pre>
</div>

</div>

</div>
</div>

</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<p>Note how <code>cents</code> is not an entire table but a single column, or a <code>GeoSeries</code> object. This means you can plot it directly, just like a table:</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">
<div class="prompt input_prompt">In&nbsp;[37]:</div>
<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython2"><pre><span class="n">cents</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">plot</span><span class="p">()</span>
</pre></div>

</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="output_wrapper">
<div class="output">


<div class="output_area"><div class="prompt output_prompt">Out[37]:</div>


<div class="output_text output_subarea output_execute_result">

</div>
